{"id":14880818,"mediaExerciseId":"5864a723-1a7a-4c4b-a047-859313e903e9","exerciseName":"23","chapterName":"3","chapterTitle":"Working with Financial Statements","groupId":612275,"groupTitle":"Questions and Problems","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":87,"solutions":[{"id":5970597,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we are required to determine the cash coverage ratio for Pop Evil Inc.â€™s.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/c8a1ab42b2cefa6a152ce346a73efde2/25a99c602a811c4937156201e34276e9/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/c8a1ab42b2cefa6a152ce346a73efde2/25a99c602a811c4937156201e34276e9/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Before we begin, let us first define cash coverage ratio.\n\n**Cash coverage ratio** is a financial ratio that shows if the company has the ability to cover its interest expense and to determine if there are sufficient funds to pay interest and generate a profit.\n\nThe formula is denoted as follows:\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\textbf{Cash coverage ratio}& =\n \\dfrac{\\text{EBIT + Depreciation Expense}} {\\text{Interest Expense}}\\\\ \\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":274,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/c8a1ab42b2cefa6a152ce346a73efde2/8d3a9cbbd845d28478d7a8d3b6cc8ca8/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":138,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/c8a1ab42b2cefa6a152ce346a73efde2/8d3a9cbbd845d28478d7a8d3b6cc8ca8/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Before we can determine the cash coverage ratio, first we need to determine the earnings before taxes or EBT:\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\textbf{EBT}& =\n \\dfrac{\\text{Net income}} {\\text{100\\% - Tax rate}}\\\\ \\\\\n& = \\frac{\\$16,481} {100\\% - 34\\%}\\\\ \\\\\n& = \\frac{\\$16,481} {1.00 - 0.34}\\\\ \\\\\n&= \\boxed{\\$24,971.21}\\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\\\nAs can be seen, the EBT is $24,971.21.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"Next is to determine EBIT:\n\n$$\\begin{array}{l r}\\\\\n\\text{EBT} & \\text{\\$24,971.21}\\\\\n\\text{Add: Interest Expense} & \\text{3,681.00}\\\\  \\hline\n\\textbf{EBIT}&\\boxed{\\$28,652.21}\\\\ \\\\\n\\end{array}$$\n\\\nAs can be seen, the EBIT is $28,652.21.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"Finally, to determine the cash coverage ratio:\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\textbf{Cash coverage ratio}& =\n \\dfrac{\\text{EBIT + Depreciation Expense}} {\\text{Interest Expense}}\\\\ \\\\\n& = \\frac{\\$28,652.21 + \\$4,385} {\\$3,681}\\\\ \\\\\n&= \\boxed{8.98}\\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\\\nIn conclusion, the cash coverage ratio is 8.98.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":408,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/c8a1ab42b2cefa6a152ce346a73efde2/28a79a3da980d2eac357f85bfacebb6e/lateximg_large.png","width":872},"regular":{"height":205,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/c8a1ab42b2cefa6a152ce346a73efde2/28a79a3da980d2eac357f85bfacebb6e/lateximg.png","width":436}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"8.98","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":22,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/c8a1ab42b2cefa6a152ce346a73efde2/388ea641347bf097161d1affcb53a2f1/lateximg_large.png","width":51},"regular":{"height":11,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/c8a1ab42b2cefa6a15